{"/service/ndnp/iune/batch_iune_bismuth_ver01/data/sn2008060406/00332898176/1920073001/0400.xml":{"full_text":"JWZU l\nThe American Issue i\nIllinois Edition\nVolume XV WESTERVILLE, OHIO, JULY 30, 1920 lumber 16\nPETITIONS HAVE BEEN FILED\nBY MANY WET CANDIDATES FOR\nCONGRESS AND STATE LEGISLATURE\nNearly All Wet Leaders in Last Legislature Are Seeking\nRe-Election\nLIST OF CANDIDATES REMOVES ALL DOUBT\nTHAT LIQUOR INTERESTS WILL FIGHT HARD\nBritten and Burke Announce Platforms Opposing the Volstead Act\nTHE FIRST AND MOST IMPORTANT FIGHT IS ON SEPTEMBER 15\nFinal proof that the wets arc planning to fight for the passage of beer\nand wine legislation in Congress and the various state legislatures is con\ntained in the list of candidates who have tiled for nomination at the primaries.\nPractically all legislators who voted wet in the last legislature are can\ndidates for re-election. Enough additional wet candidates have already filed\nfor the state legislature to make it certain that the House of Representatives\nwill be wet unless the drys put up a desperate fight for endorsed dry candi\ndates at the primary election on September 15.\nFamous Wet Has Filed\nLee O\u2019Neil Browne, for years the\nfloor leader of the wets on the Demo\ncratic side in the House, is a candidate\n\u2022for re-election. If lie wins there is\njittli doubt that he will use his in\nU fluence, his voice, and his vote to op\npose all measures favorable to Pro\nhibition enforcement.\nCurran a Candidate\nTom Curran, Chicago cx-saloon\nkeeper and floor leader of the liquor\nforces on the Republican side, has\nfiled for re-nomination. If he wins it\nis hardly to lie expected that he and\nhis associates whom lie controls polit\nically will use their legislative power\nto protect the one-half of 1 per cent\nlimit in the state enforcement law or\notherwise favor enforcement legisla\ntion.\nWet Ginders of Dry Rockford\nRunning\nGuy Ginders of the Rockford dis\ntrict is again a candidate. Guy Gin\nders was authorized to represent the\nbanner dry district in the state. He\nwas the legal representative of the\ncitizens of Rockford\u2014-dry Rockford\nthe pioneer large dry city of the na\nfion. Ginders promised to vote for\nlaw enforcement legislation in the last\nsession, but voted with the wets in\nstead. He may succeed again. If he\ndoes there is no reason to believe\nfrom his past record that lie will not\nagain vote with the wets of Chicago,\nEast St. Louis and Peoria for legisla\ntion desired by the wets and against\nlegislation desired by the drvs.\nJoliet Wets\u2019 Representative Up\nMichael E. Hcnnibry of the Eorty\nfirst District in which Joilet is located\nhas filed for re-nomination on the\nDemocratic ticket. Henncbry lias al\nways voted the wet program straight,\ncarrying out the wishes of the Joilet\nsaloonkeepers. Although Joilet is\nnow dry under the Eighteenth\nAmendment, there is little prospect\nthat Hennebry will depart from his\ncustom of voting with the wets on\nevery roll call, if he is sent back to\nSpringfield.\nMany Other Wet Candidates\nClarence Jones of Springfield has\nfiled on the Democratic ticket. Sid\nney Lyon of Chicago, a Republican,\nwho fiercely but futilcly protested\nagainst ratification and enforcement\nmeasures lias filed. Ferdinand A.\n(iaresche of Madison is again a can\ndidate. Bathroom Bob Wilson here\ntofore elected and re-clccted from the\ndistrict containing the dry city of\nEvanston because so many drys\n'failed to vote at the primaries has\nfiled his petition. David E. Shana\nhan, Republican, of Chicago, Speaker\ni of the House during the last session\nI has filed for re-nomination. All of\nthe above wrho are but a few of those\nup for re-nomination who voted wet\nlast time are being counted upon by\nthe wets in their announced purpose\nto wipe out the Illinois enforcement\nlaw.\nWet Congressional Candidates\nFred A. Britten of Chicago who in\nthe last Congress introduced a beer\nand wine bill is a candiadte for re\nnomination. In announcing bis plat\nform he declared that the would work\nto liberalize the Volstead enforcement\nlaw. Robert Emmett Burke lias filed\nhis petition as a candidate for the\nDemocratic nomination for United\nStates Senator. The Chicago Trib\nune article announcing bis candidacy\nsays, \"He is anti-the Eighteenth\nAmendment and all forms of enforce\nment laws having to do with the liq\nuor question.\u201d\nI Nation-Wide Beer and Wine Fight\nJn Illinois the situation is much the\nI same as in Pennsylvania. Illinois is\nlone of the large states selected by\nI the liquor interests as the chief battlc\nj ground for beer and wine. The Phil\nadelphia North American recently\nstated that in nearly every congrcs\njsional district in Pennsylvania men\n|are found seeking election as the!\n\u25a0champions of the outlawed rum traffic,\ni It says:\n\u201cIn a large number of districts, in-!\n\u2018deed, there are several candidates run-i\njning on this platform, all backed by\ni liquor money. They include both\nDemocrats and Republicans. Four of\nthe five machine-approved Republican\ncandidates for Congress-at-large are\nknown supporters of the liquor cause,\nla fact which enables the state organ!-,\nzation to demand substantial contri\nbutions from the interests striving to\nundermine the Prohibition law. A\nI similar situation is apparent in New\nJersey and elsewhere.\u201d\nOnly Six Weeks Left\nIn the short time remaining between\nnow and primaries on September 15\nthe drys must organize for effective,\nconcerted action at the polls to pro\ntect Prohibition. Apathetic, disintcr\n'ested drys\u2014drys who think the fight\nis over must be made to realize the\nimportance of voting at the primaries.!\nAll drys must be informed as to the j\nright candidates to support. They\n'must be warned against dividing the\ndry vote among too many candidates.;\nI They must be advised of the endorse-:\nIntents of the Anti-Saloon League for\nI their respective districts. There are j\nenough drys to win. But they must\nvote right and unitedly on September!\n15th or the wets will succeed in car-!\ntying out their program.\n_\nVote for indorsed dry legislative\ncandidates at the Primary election on\nSeptember 15.\n\nE. H. Gary Declares\nProhibition Benefits\nIndustry and Labor\nBetter Conditions Due To Dry Laws\nSays Steel Corporation Head\nThe July 3yd Chicago Daily News\nprinted the following Associated\nPress Dispatch from New York:\n\u201cProhibition has been beneficial to\nthe nation\u2019s industrial and economic\n1 life in the opinion of Elbert H. Gary,\nhead of the United States Steel Cor\nporation, who issued a statement here\nlast night on the eve of his departure\n1 for Europe, giving his views on the j\nbusiness outlook generally.\n\u2018The Prohibition laws have had!\nmarked effect,\u2019 he said. \u2018In nearly;\nevery newspaper one will read of\nfewrr inmates of prisons, almshouses\nand hospitals, and larger balances in\nj savings institutions and better, clean\ncr and healthier conditions in the\ndwellings, all on account of Prohibi\ntion. Testimony on this subject is\naccumulated day by day. From an\neconomic and pecuniary standpoint I\nthink a large majority of the people\nof this country are in favor of Prohi\nbition and it is pleasing to note that\nthe large number of workmen, so far\nas I am informed, subscribe to this\nview.\u2019\n_\nThe Coming Legislative Campaign\nA Call for Loyalty afld Activity\nBy F. Scott McBride, State Superintendent of the Anti-Saloon League\nIt is now less than two months until Primary Day which comes\non Wednesday, September 15th.\nThe wets are unusually active this year. They are determined\nto break down the law enforcement machinery of the state. Their\nprogram is to repeal the law enforcement legislation of the state, to\nrefuse what appropriations are necessary to make the Eighteenth\nAmendment effective and to enact a peer and wine law, asking for\nthe sale of 2/ per cent beer, thus preparing to nullify the Eight\neenth Amendment to the Constitution. They realize that they must\nwin this fight in Congress as well as fit ft state Legislatures before it\nwill be effective, but they are out to win both in this primary.\nThe worst feature of the situation is the fact that while the\nwets are more active than ordinarily, he drys are resting in a false\nsecurity that inasmuch as Prohibition is now a part of the Constitu\ntion the fight is over.\nProhibition Will BetChief Issue\nThe wet and dry issue is sure to fcj the chief issue of the coming\nprimary. Wet candidates have filed in practically every legislative\ndistrict within the bounds of the sti'.te. These candidates, while\nj pledged to the wets, are doing what they can to continue the apathy\nl of the drys by saying that now the drys need not oppose them inas\nmuch as the wet and dry question is settled, but at the same time\nthe wet organizations and wet candidates are in the field seeking\nnomination. These candidates are pledging themselves to the nulli\nj fication program of the wets.\nA second danger is that more drys are crowding into the field\nthan ever before because of personal ambitions to go to the Legis\nI lature. As the dry movement becomes more popular dry candi\ndates naturally become more plentiful. This will split up the dry\nvote and make it easy for the wet candidates to crowd in where two\nyears ago they found no chance. The vets are not making this\nblunder but are putting in the field only enough candidates to give\nthem their best chance to win.\nShall the Session of 1921 be a Repetition of the Session of 1909?\nProbably the wettest House Illinois has ever had was the Leg\nislature of 1909 known as the \u201cJiick-pot\u201d Legislature. It followed\nimmediately the session that passed our first local option law. The\nfact that the session of 1909 was the wettest one we have ever had\nwas not because the local option law was in any way a failure\u2014\nit was a great success\u2014but for that reason the wets were more\nactive and because of their recent victory the drys felt secure and\nthe result was that because of the indifference of the dry voters of\nthe state the wets controlled the Houpe, repealed the local option\nlaw and disgraced the state with corruption.\nDrys Must Continue Loyal and Active\nI do not need to recall to the atcfinltort of the 'drys that many\nof the large cities of the state after voting dry, usually for the same\nreason cited above, slipped back into the wet column before the\ndrys were awake to the fact that they must stand guard in every\nprimary and every election. It\" we are to avoid a recurrence of these\nexperiences this year after we have won the great victory there will\nhave to be an awakening on the part of the drys of the state. Xu\nevidence of this awakening has so far appeared. It must come\nquickly as it is now less than sixty days until primary day. It will\nbe a tragedy if, after more than half a century of hard fighting\nwhich has given to us the victory, through indifference anil careless\nness we permit this octopus to secure again its deadly hold upon\nour state and country.\nMr. Dry, what will be your answer? If we are to win every\ndistrict must have sufficient candidates, but only enough, to give us\nthe best chance to win. If we are to win the dry voters must sup\nport only such candidates as are endorsed by the Anti-Saloon\nLeague, the organization carrying the responsibility for the organ\nized legislative fight.\nThere never has been a call for loyalty and activity more urgent\nthan the call that comes this year.\nProhibition Hotel Aid\nS. W. Straus Declares\nProhibition is proving a blessing to\nAmerican hotels, says S. W. Straus,\nexecutive head of the Ambassador\nHotels System,\n\"In the old days,\u201d he says, \u201cthe\nhotel business, generally speaking, was\nunder a certain moral cloud. It was\nrecognized that the average hotel de\npended on its bar and drinks served\nto its guests in their rooms for a con\nsiderable part of its earnings.\n'The high class American hotel to\nday supplies home environment.\nAbove everything else there must be\na wholesome moral tone, which could\nnot have been possible before the es\ntablishment of Prohibition.\n\u201cThe next few years will witness\nan era of new hotel construction, be\ncause of the fact that now a man\ncan live in a hotel with his family\nand feel that the surrounding influ\nences conform to his highest ideals.\u201d\n\u2014Chicago Herald Examiner.\nVote for indorsed dry legislative\ncandidates at the Primary election on\nSeptember 15.\nWhy the Wets Want the Drys to Stay Away\nFrom the Polls on Primary Election\nDay, September 15\nAgain must we remember that even with a wet President\nand a wet Congress, that would amend the Volstead act to\ngive light wines and beer to the people, yet we in Illinois have\na search and seizure law that must be wiped out before\nwe can be benefited by national legislation.\u2014From address by\nFred Rhode, president of the Cook County Liquor Dealers\u2019\nAssociation, at its annual convention on June 24, 1920.\nTo protect the Illinois Prohibition enforcement law and\nto make possible the passage of other legislation in support of\nthe Eighteenth Amendment, VOTE FOR ENDORSED\nDRY LEGISLATIVE CANDIDATES AT THE PRIMARY\nELECTION ON SEPTEMBER 15.\nONE YEAR OF PROHIBITION\nBRINGS WONDERFUL BENEFITS\nTO THE CITY OF STREAM\nSurvey by Reporter Reveals Some of the Great Good Done\nby Dry Law\nBANKS BUSY, MERCHANTS PROSPEROUS,\nLABOR CONTENTED AND HOMES HAPPY\nAll Prophecies of Dry Disaster Failed to Come True, as They Have\nEverywhere Else\nPERMANENT PROHIBITION DEPENDS ON SEPTEMBER 15 PRIMARIES\nWhen America went dry Streator\ntrembled. Streator was wet. Streator!\n'is a city of 1S,00U located in LaSalle!\n'county, Illinois. Streator is a rail-i\nroad center, a mining and manufac-j\nluring town surrounded by rich farm-1\ning country. Foreigners make up a!\nlarge proportion of its population.\nWhen America went dry Streator\nhad sixty-eight saloons. When tin\nsaloons were closed on July 1, 1919,\nthe usual prophecies of disaster were j\nmale. A year went by. In a series]\nof articles by W. J. Lewis in the\nStreator Daily Independent Times\nthe story of what Prohibition meant\nto Strrator is clearly and compre-;\nhensively told. It is based on a\nthorough survey of local conditions\nand a great many interviews of local\npersons by Mr. Lewis. His report\nis the most complete review of Pro-1\nhibition results by any Illinois news-]\npaper that has come to the attention\nof the Issue.\nWhat Streator Feared\nUntil a complete survey of nation-]\nal Prohibition results can be made\nthe best answer to the question, Is\nProhibition making good in Anier-1\nica?\" is the report of results in in\ndividual cities. We arc therefore]\ngiving as many extracts as space will]\npermit from the above mentioned\narticles telling how the dry law af-j\nfected Streator.\nA year ago they said nearly 70\nbuildings in Streator will be empty.\nMerchants will lose trade. The city\nwill go broke. Labor will slack in\nits efforts when deprived of personal\nliberty. There would be a depres\nsion of business.\nWhat Really Happened\nThe following is quoted from the\nIndependent Times:\n\u201cStreator\u2019s first concern, on realiz\ning that John was dead, was her fi\nnancial status, for in return for the\nhalf million or more which he swal\nlowed out of the coffers, purses and\nstockings of local interests, John\ngenerously gave back some odd thirty\nthousand dollars in return. In other\nwords, the saloon paid out about $.12,\n000 in taxes to the city of Streator,!\nand, of course, that was cut off. The\ncity, like any human being shorn of\nits income or a big share of it, com-'\nI menced to figure out how it could\nbe met; and took steps to meet it.\nDespite the arguments to the con\ntrary, Streator is not in a state of\nbankruptcy, neither will mortgages\nj have to be taken on the municipality\nI to pay the salaries of the aldermen.\nJ Within a short time the city accord\ning to local city officials and former\ni officials, will be in an excellent finan\ncial condition and the thirty-two\n1 thousand dollars paid yearly by the\nsaloons will not be missed, be\ncause its place will have been taken\nby moneys from other sources.\u201d\nSavings Accounts Increase\n\u201cA local banker informed the repor\nter that his institution is doing a\nbigger savings business than it ever\ndid before. Bigger, not only in the\namount of money, but in per cent of\nthe total clearings which his bank\nhandles. The savings are, to a great\nextent, the banker stated, coming\nfrom women and children and young\nmen. Note the mentioning of the\nchildren. Children can\u2019t earn money;\nat least not in Streator. It must be\ngiven to them, and the father is the\ngiver\u2014either the father or other male\nmembers of the faily who have as\nsumed, in many cases, a new obliga\ntion during the past twelve months.\nThe fathers and brothers, then, have\nit to give; therefore there must be a\nsurplus over the weekly or monthly\nexpenses of living. A vastly different\nstory, the banker pointed out, when\ncompared with the tales and trails j\nwhich in former years too often dis\nappeared into the stained saw-dust\nbehind the twin doors.\nLabor Earns More\n\u201cMany will state that this saving is\ndue to the fact that the average man\nis earning much more this year than\nhe did before Prohibition went into\neffect. This is true, the banker ex\nplained, but \u2018pays\u2019 are only of a\ncomparative value\u2014their worth is\njudged by what they arc able to pur\nchase. In relation, then, to the cost\nof living today the average \u2018pay\u2019 of\ntoday is no greater than the \u2018pay\u2019 of\nformer years when the cost of living\nwas figured out in much smaller fig\nures. In former years, when prices\nwere low, \u2018pays\u2019 were low, and sav\nings were low\u2014where the surplus\nwent for the gratification of the\nearner\u2019s appetite for drink. In these\ndays prices are high, so are wages,\nand the surplus has increased cor\nrespondingly. But the reporter was\nshown, the surplus is handled in a\ndifferent way than before Prohibition\ncame into effect. One of the \u2018chief\navaiues of escape,\u2019 has been com\npletely blocked; the \u2018cornered* sur\nplus partly goes out through other\ngates\u2014legitimately spending\u2014and the\nrest has found a new gate, the sav\nings bank.\"\nBusiness Depression and Empty Stores\n\"Business depression and vacant\nbuildings\u2014this was another cry of\nthe alarmist during the interment of\nJohn.\nThe person who can find many va\ncant buildings in Streator is some\none whom many would-be renters is\ntrying to find. One need ty take a\ntrip down Main street and lie will see\nthis so-called \u2018avenue of vacant\nsto'es.\u2019 There is not a vacant store\non Main street, unless it may be some\ndilapidated place awaiting the day\nwhen it shall be torn down to give\nplace to a modern structure. All the\nbuddings vacated by the saloons in\nthe business district have been taken\nover by other businesses, or have been\ncontinued as housing quarters for\nsoft drink parlors and lunch counters.\nSwinging doors are missing; they are\nneeded no more. In outlying ditricts\na few of the buildings are vacant,\nbut the most of them have been taken\nover by other forms of business. And\nthe loss in rents of those few vacant\nplaces is practically clown to the zero\nmark, when compared with the in\ncrease in the money traffic made pos\nsible through the new places.\n\u201cOver a dozen new store fronts, im\nprovements on the interior, nearly\nthat many new stores, several new\nbuildings, a new theatre under way,\nreal estate business booming, mer\nchants enjoying an unheard of busi\nness, imports increased several hun\ndred per cent, export of local articles\non a similar increase\u2014this is the\nbusiness depression that was feared.\u201d\nBusiness Man\u2019s Testimony\nThe reporter quotes a Streator\nbusiness man as follows:\n\u201cI think that I can state off-hand\nthat Prohibition lias brought cash\nsales up fifty per cent, and has estab\nlished a credit system that is that\nmuch more efficient. In former years\nI often had customers come to me\nwho would \u2018beg off\u2019 from paying\ntheir bills, stating that they had more\nurgent debts to attend to. I knew\nwhat those urgent debts were. They\nwere, in many cases, saloon bills. A\nman would neglect his grocery or\nclo'hing bill to pay a saloon-keeper\u2014\nif he didn\u2019t, he would be cut off. They\nare better dressed; they buy better\nthings; they are enjoying life more;\nthe relation between the customer and\nthe merchant has entered onto a\nbasis of clearer understanding in\nwhich the one realizes the true pur\nTo Defeat the Beer and Wine Program of the Wets Vote for Indorsed Dry\nLegislative and Congressional Candidates at Primary Election Sept. 15","height":"26852","width":"17924"}}
